definition.value: Combining with gonadotropin-releasing hormone to initiate a change in cell activity. Gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) is a peptide hormone responsible for the release of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH) from the anterior pituitary. GnRH is synthesized and released by the hypothalamus.

Combining with histamine to initiate a change in cell activity. Histamine is a physiologically active amine, found in plant and animal tissue and released from mast cells as part of an allergic reaction in humans.
Catalysis of the transmembrane transfer of an ion by a channel that opens when glutamate has been bound by the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.
An ionotropic glutamate receptor activity that exhibits fast gating by glutamate and acts by opening a cation channel permeable to sodium, potassium, and, in the absence of a GluR2 subunit, calcium.
An ionotropic glutamate receptor activity that exhibits slow gating by glutamate, acts by opening a nonselective cation channel, and can be activated by L-aspartate.

Combining with a leukotriene to initiate a change in cell activity. Leukotrienes are pharmacologically active substances with a set of three conjugated double bonds -  some contain a peptide group based on cysteine.
Combining with melanocortin to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with corticotropin to initiate a change in cell activity.

Combining with beta-endorphin, and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein. Beta-endorphin is a peptide, 31 amino acids long, resulting from processing of the precursor proopiomelanocortin (POMC).
Combining with melanocyte-stimulating hormone to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with an N-formyl peptide to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with neuropeptide Y to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with an odorant and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity in response to detection of smell.
Combining with an opioid (any narcotic derived from or resembling opium), and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein.

Combining with the biogenic amine octopamine to initiate a change in cell activity. Octopamine is found in both vertebrates and invertebrates and can have properties both of a hormone and a neurotransmitter and acts as an adrenergic agonist.
Combining with oxytocin to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with parathyroid hormone to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with platelet activating factor to initiate a change in cell activity.

Combining with the biogenic amine serotonin and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein. Serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine) is a neurotransmitter and hormone found in vertebrates and invertebrates.

Combining with somatostatin to initiate a change in cell activity. Somatostatin is a peptide hormone that regulates the endocrine system by signaling via G-protein coupled somatostatin receptors. Somatostatin has two active forms produced by proteolytic cleavage -  a 14 amino acid peptide (SST-14) and a 28 amino acid peptide (SST-28).
Combining with a tachykinin neuropeptide and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein.
Combining with thyroid-stimulating hormone to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with thyrotropin-releasing hormone to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining selectively with transferrin, and delivering transferrin into the cell via endocytosis. Transferrin is a major iron carrier protein in vertebrates.
Combining with vasoactive intestinal polypeptide to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with vasopressin to initiate a change in cell activity.

label.value: transmembrane receptor protein tyrosine phosphatase activity

definition.value: Combining with a signal and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction -  protein tyrosine phosphate + H2O -eq- protein tyrosine + phosphate.
Combining with an ephrin to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with a GPI-anchored ephrin to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with a transmembrane ephrin to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with an epidermal growth factor and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with a fibroblast growth factor and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with hepatocyte growth factor and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with insulin and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with insulin-like growth factor and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.

Combining with macrophage colony-stimulating factor (M-CSF) and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + a protein-L-tyrosine -eq- ADP + a protein-L-tyrosine phosphate.
Combining with platelet-derived growth factor and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with platelet-derived growth factor isoform PDGF-AA, PDGF-BB or PDGF-AB to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with platelet-derived growth factor isoform PDGF-BB or PDGF-AB to initiate a change in cell activity.

Combining with stem cell factor (SCF) and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + a protein-L-tyrosine -eq- ADP + a protein-L-tyrosine phosphate. Stem cell factor is a cytokine that stimulates mast cell growth and differentiation.

label.value: vascular endothelial growth factor-activated receptor activity

definition.value: Combining with a vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) and transmitting the signal across the plasma membrane to initiate a change in cell activity.

label.value: transforming growth factor beta-activated receptor activity

definition.value: Combining with a transforming growth factor beta (TGFbeta) and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction -  ATP protein serine -eq- ADP + protein serine phosphate, and ATP + protein threonine -eq- ADP + protein threonine phosphate.

label.value: transforming growth factor beta receptor activity, type I

definition.value: Combining with a complex of transforming growth factor beta and a type II TGF-beta receptor to initiate a change in cell activity -  upon binding, acts as a downstream transducer of TGF-beta signals.

label.value: transforming growth factor beta receptor activity, type II

definition.value: Combining with transforming growth factor beta to initiate a change in cell activity -  upon ligand binding, binds to and catalyzes the phosphorylation of a type I TGF-beta receptor.
Combining with a neurotrophin, any of a family of growth factors that prevent apoptosis in neurons and promote nerve growth, and transmitting the signal to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with tumor necrosis factor, a proinflammatory cytokine produced by monocytes and macrophages, to initiate a change in cell function.
Sensing extracellular osmolarity to initiate a change in cell activity, and spanning the membrane of the cell.
Combining with an extracellular messenger (called a death ligand), and transmitting the signal from one side of the plasma membrane to the other to initiate apoptotic or necrotic cell death.
Combining with an extracellular messenger (death ligand) without transmission of the signal. Decoy death receptors compete with death receptors for ligand binding, and do not initiate apoptosis.
Combining with a low-density lipoprotein particle and delivering the low-density lipoprotein into the cell via endocytosis.
